programme.title: Ice Road Truckers
programme.desc: S8 E11 Journey To The End Of The Earth For two months out of every year, a group of exceptional men find their way to the Canadian tundra to undertake one of the most dangerous jobs on earth. In the thick of winter, truckers in giant eighteen wheelers carry vital equipment and supplies to miners hundreds of miles away. In blizzard conditions, these truckers travel over ice roads that often take them over frozen lakes. Each man is trained in self survival, from fixing his truck in sub zero conditions in seconds to escaping from a truck if the ice cracks. On the other end of the journey are miners whose lives depend on the truckers making it to their base, year after year. The episodes will form a narrative arch - taking the viewer on a journey from when the experienced and novice truckers first sign up for the season, to the last truck making it back to base.

programme.title: American Restoration
programme.desc: S4 E20 Call The Count Rick Dale, one of Pawn Stars' most popular experts, runs Las Vegas based Rick's Restorations, a family business that finds, restores and upcycles cool objects ranging from Cadillacs to Coke Machines. The before and after reveals of his work are always highlights, in part because of the history nuggets Rick Dale shares about each object, whether it's a barber chair or a gas pump. In this spinoff series, featuring the dynamic characters at Rick's workplace, viewers will watch a variety of objects be bought, bartered and transformed, learning the process of restoration; how do you duplicate Coke machine red? Where can you find 1920s tires? A storyteller who works with tools instead of a pen, Rick shares when and why objects were invented, who used them and how fixing or transforming them changes their value.

programme.title: Outback Truckers
programme.desc: S8 E5 Episode 5 Steve Grahame is sending one of his best mates, Slick, to face the hostility of the outback. It's the last desert run before Christmas and Slick's promised his family he'll definitely make it home, he just has to do a 1900 kilometre trek through the Central Australian desert first. In drought ravaged New South Wales Chaz Butt is making a mercy run delivering much needed hay and water to give farmers a fighting chance of survival during the biggest dry spell in half a century.

programme.title: Outback Truckers
programme.desc: S8 E6 Episode 6 In the Northern Territory the Water Drillers, Anthony and Danyelle Haigh, enlist a new team member as family life on the road puts their marriage to the test. Slick's cross country race home for Christmas looks to be slipping out of reach. A last minute order for three more trailers of building supplies means he has to do the entire journey again. In Southern Queensland rookie cattle trucker Kylie Hornick has her first crack at driving a triple road train, transporting 800 head of cattle while husband David tries some backseat driving.

programme.title: Black Ops

programme.title: Ice Road Truckers
programme.desc: S8 E12 World's End For two months out of every year, a group of exceptional men find their way to the Canadian tundra to undertake one of the most dangerous jobs on earth. In the thick of winter, truckers in giant eighteen wheelers carry vital equipment and supplies to miners hundreds of miles away. In blizzard conditions, these truckers travel over ice roads that often take them over frozen lakes. Each man is trained in self survival, from fixing his truck in sub zero conditions in seconds to escaping from a truck if the ice cracks. On the other end of the journey are miners whose lives depend on the truckers making it to their base, year after year. The episodes will form a narrative arch - taking the viewer on a journey from when the experienced and novice truckers first sign up for the season, to the last truck making it back to base.

programme.title: American Restoration
programme.desc: S4 E21 Harrison's Vendorlator Rick Dale, one of Pawn Stars' most popular experts, runs Las Vegas based Rick's Restorations, a family business that finds, restores and upcycles cool objects ranging from Cadillacs to Coke Machines. The before and after reveals of his work are always highlights, in part because of the history nuggets Rick Dale shares about each object, whether it's a barber chair or a gas pump. In this spinoff series, featuring the dynamic characters at Rick's workplace, viewers will watch a variety of objects be bought, bartered and transformed, learning the process of restoration; how do you duplicate Coke machine red? Where can you find 1920s tires? A storyteller who works with tools instead of a pen, Rick shares when and why objects were invented, who used them and how fixing or transforming them changes their value.

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S1 E7 Episode 7 Rick explores one of Cornwall's hidden secrets, the secluded and stunning Fowey Estuary, joining his friend on a boat trip to learn about the history of the area and getting a unique view of the beautiful buildings along the river bank. Downstream, after a meal of crab scotch eggs at a fashionable new restaurant, Rick discovers that the historic town of Fowey was once a hotbed of piracy. Just above the town is a family making a prize-winning Cornish vodka, which Rick uses to make a delicious pancake with a wild blackberry compote and Cornish clotted cream.

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S1 E8 Episode 8 On the wild north Atlantic coast, Rick heads out to sea to go fishing for lobsters with his old friend and celebrity chef Nathan Outlaw, and learns about a revolutionary new conservation programme which is making lobster fishing a sustainable enterprise. In the historic and pretty harbour town of Port Isaac, Rick and Nathan cook up a fabulous Lobster risotto. At Tresillian House, near Newquay, Rick meets with head gardener John Harris, to find out more about his Victorian walled garden, an oasis of calm, where Rick discovers how harvesting by the phases of the moon means better tasting veg. Rick cooks a Cornish Briam, a tasty slow-cooked dish of fresh vegetables.

programme.title: Inside the Factory
programme.desc: S6 E6 Malt Loaf Malt loaf has been a popular teatime treat for more than 80 years; these days we get through a staggering 130 million of them every year. So to get to grips with how this sweet and squidgy cake cum bread is made, Gregg Wallace is rolling up his sleeves to get stuck in, following a production line of massive dough mixing, mind-boggling tin filling and intensely hot baking. Meanwhile, historian Ruth Goodman reveals the surprising story of a British baking company that cooked up the first usiness computer, as well as visiting Cambridgeshire to find out how wheat flour was ground the traditional way, until the Victorians demand for white bread brought about the demise of Britain's iconic windmills.

programme.title: The Chocolate Queen
programme.desc: S3 E1 Episode 1 Returning for a third season, Kirsten Tibballs, aka The Chocolate Queen is back! Celebrated pastry chef and famous chocolatier, Tibballs presents an array of incredibly clever and innovative tricks, tips and cheats to bring the wow factor to home baking. Kirsten believes chocolate is the key to happiness, and with a selection of delectable desserts easy to recreate in home kitchens, she may just be right. Kirsten is sharing recipes and techniques for everything from a next-level take on white chocolate & peanut parfait to her rich chocolate flan. In series three of The Chocolate Queen, Tibballs shares a wealth of knowledge as she works through a huge range of recipes, ensuring even beginner bakers can successfully enjoy her creations at home.

programme.title: Mary Berry's Quick Cooking
programme.desc: S1 E4 Navy Mary is off to join the Navy on-board one of its most powerful warships, the HMS Defender, learning how they turn out hundreds of meals a day against the clock and on a tight budget. Whilst the crew run a war training exercise on board the ship, Mary heads to the galley to see if she can help the kitchen team with the mammoth task of prepping, cooking, and serving 240 meals, from scratch, in just 75minutes. Known as 'Action messing' Mary is really cooking against the clock. In her own kitchen, Mary creates dishes inspired by her experience at sea; a tempting Crumble Fish Pie, Special Cauliflower Soup and moreish Mini Sausage Rolls.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E2 French Maeve meets up with top chef Guillaume Brahimi, owner and chef of Bennelong Restaurant at the Sydney Opera House. He gives the rundown on the essential French ingredients: great butter and salt (both French), bread, fresh herbs, mustard, and cheeses. He cooks up a beef bourguignon and shares the secrets of the perfect potato mash. Former chef France Vidal makes a French onion soup in half an hour, TV chef Gabriel Gate gives the rundown on essential cooking equipment and makes an easy summer dessert using raspberries, while renowned chef Philippe Mouchel (Philippe Mouchel at The Brasserie, Melbourne) shows his knife work. programme.title: Inside the Factory
programme.desc: S6 E6 Malt Loaf Malt loaf has been a popular teatime treat for more than 80 years; these days we get through a staggering 130 million of them every year. So to get to grips with how this sweet and squidgy cake cum bread is made, Gregg Wallace is rolling up his sleeves to get stuck in, following a production line of massive dough mixing, mind-boggling tin filling and intensely hot baking. Meanwhile, historian Ruth Goodman reveals the surprising story of a British baking company that cooked up the first usiness computer, as well as visiting Cambridgeshire to find out how wheat flour was ground the traditional way, until the Victorians demand for white bread brought about the demise of Britain's iconic windmills.

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S2 E10 Episode 10 In our fields and hedgerows are plants that are delicious, and plants that are deadly, as Rick learns from a professional forager who takes him on a tour around the beautiful Camel Estuary. Inspired, Rick creates his own version of a Greek 'Horta' pie with foraged greens. Then it's a trip down memory lane with his long-time fish supplier Matthew Stevens who remembers Cornwall before the tourists came. Over a pint with actor, comedian and passionate Cornishman Ed Rowe, star of the BAFTA winning film Bait, Rick examines the impact of second home ownership on Cornish communities.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E3 French Guillaume Brahimi from Guillaume at Bennelong, at the Sydney Opera House, gives a guide to essential fresh ingredients, from herbs to vegetables, then shows how to cook the perfect steak and the potatoes that are a staple through Parisian bistros. Philippe Mouchel (Philippe Mouchel at The Brasserie, Melbourne) makes a lamb navarin served with a celeriac and truffle puree. Maeve meets cheese expert Eric Moschietto from La Bergerie cheese shop in Melbourne and learns that there are so many French cheeses, you can taste three a day for a year and still have some to try. Top food stylist Marie Helene Clauson draws on family recipes to create a light cheese souffle, and charcuterer Romeo Badouin explains terrines, pates and confit. We meet the food and beverage manager at the Sofitel Hotel Sydney, Laurent Branover, and learn that every French family has a crepe pan and uses it every Sunday to make simple crepes, or crepes Suzette served with orange Cointreau butter and flamed.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E4 Indonesian Maeve plunges into the vibrant, spicy world of Indonesian food with chef Rohanna Halim, who heads an all-women kitchen team at her restaurant Ratu Sari in suburban Sydney. She shows the key ingredients needed for Indonesian cooking, including many fresh herbs and spices now widely available. Rohanna makes a spicy chilli sauce called belado which goes perfectly with everything from prawns to vegetables. Fellow head chef and owner Alina Lucas from Jimbaran Restaurant cooks an easy chicken curry, while Java Restaurant's 'Aunty' Wahwan whips up grilled fish with a sweet-and-sour vegetable sauce. A real prince, Tjok Gde Kerthyasa, from Bali's royal family, cooks a traditional duck on the good old Aussie barbie and serves it with a fresh sambal. Also on the barbecue is a superb satay from an expatriate Dutch-Indonesian, Paul Rast. To finish, young Indonesian-Australian Ben Mochtar makes his favourite childhood dessert: eis cendol. It features shaved ice, tropical fruit, coconut milk and 'worms' made from mung bean flour.

programme.desc: S1 E1 Fish Of North Cornwall Rick looks at the many events which have influenced him over the past 25 years of cooking in Cornwell. A scrumptious celebration of the ocean's bounty.

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S2 E11 Episode 11 Rick joins a team diving for Razor Clams, which he takes back to the kitchen to make a quick but tasty dish of grilled Shangurro Clams. At the end of Newlyn Pier, Rick visits a scruffy little hut that until recently played a huge part in determining the height of everything around us. And in the Penlee Museum, Rick is shown some of the beautiful items made a century ago by fishermen using Cornish copper, and meets a metalworker who is bringing copperwork back to the town.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E5 Maltese This program explores a different take on Mediterranean cooking with the rustic delights of Maltese food. Chef Paul Camilleri (Restaurant Sojourn) goes through the essential ingredients and then cooks his family recipe for the national dish of rabbit stew. Then it's time for the national snack food, pastizzi, and the national sandwich called Hobz Biz Zejt: tomato paste on crusty bread and topped with anchovies, capers, and olive oil. Chef Louis Bigeni shows how the Maltese have modified recipes from their neighbours, taking pasta to a different level with a rich meat sauce and baked in pastry. We learn about the soft ricotta-style cheeses and harder mature cheese loved by the Maltese, and meet Polly Vella, who missed them so much when she came to Australia that she decided to learn how to make them herself. Finally, broadcaster Rita O'Dwyer from the Maltese radio program makes dessert.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E6 Pakistani Some Pakistani dishes are loved around the world, like biryani, the layered, spiced rice and meat dish. Chef Sonya Kayani makes a marvellous version of biryani using goat curry, which she layers with saffron and plain basmati rice. Restaurateur Basil Daniell runs through the key ingredients, herbs and spices, and shares a very easy lamb dumpling recipe adapted with wonton wrappers. We explore a very busy Pakistani eatery and discover the big favourites are tandoori chicken and a slow-cooked lamb and dahl dish called haleem. We meet Pakistani fast bowler Waqar Younis, who shows how Pakistani people love to eat with bread.

programme.title: Eat Well For Less
programme.desc: S5 E8 Episode 8 This week Gregg and Chris are in West Sussex to help the Blackman family. There's mum Kate who works as a Nursery Practitioner and her 3 daughters, 16-year-old Ellie, 11-year-old Charlotte and Annabelle, 9 and none of them will eat the same thing! With one daughter who is fussy about what she eats, and another who's dairy intolerant and avoids gluten, mum Kate is cooking 4 separate meals every night and unsurprisingly has fallen out of love with cooking. With Kate feeling guilty for relying on convenience food and takeaways, she has turned to Gregg and Chris for help. Can they bring the joy back into Kate's kitchen and stop her reaching for those convenience foods and takeaways? And can our couple of ex-greengrocers get the girls to fall in love with vegetables?

programme.desc: S20 E3 Episode 3 Judges Grace Dent and John Torode expect progress. Challenges: a pairs task, then a two course menu for guest diners. Only three advance to the Semi Finals, aiming for the Champion title.

programme.title: Mary Berry at 90: A Lifetime of Cooking ᴺᵉʷ
programme.desc: S1 E1 Tom Allen Dame Mary Berry takes a fond look back at her career in food while bringing viewers incredible mouth-watering recipes to try at home. Mary can trace her passion for outdoor cooking back 80 years, when she became a Girl Guide. Her friend, comedian Tom Allen, shares her love of the countryside but perhaps not the same aptitude for cooking. Together, they take a leisurely boat ride, sharing tales and facing the odd challenge as Tom attempts to drive the boat and navigate a lock. They stop along the way to cook Mary's classic pan-fried cod, which she learnt to make at college, and the star pudding of Mary's childhood, bread and butter pudding using her mother's recipe, which she still loves eating anywhere. Mary also makes her brand new Thai chicken traybake and her reinvention of her 1970s cottage pie with a modern mash. Spending time with Tom is a chance for Mary to share some rarely seen TV archive footage of her early attempts at outdoor cooking, showing how much things have changed.

programme.title: House Hunters Renovation

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S13 E8 Aberdeen Revisits Kirstie and Phil are back in Buckinghamshire with Emma and Andrew who are living with Emma's parents while they search for a 'forever' home. In Aberdeenshire Karen and Russell who want to cut down the commute, and get closer to open rural space.

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E1 Harrow And Herts Rupreet and Sundeep are still living at home following their wedding 18 months ago, and have managed to save a healthy deposit for their future family home. Trouble is, Rupreet is a self-confessed postcode snob and she's taken her obsession with location to the limit. When she turns up to meet Kirstie armed with a map and a set of highlighters, you know there is going to be trouble. With a 380,000-pounds budget, they should be able to find a house to fit - if Rupreet can be persuaded to look past her postcode comfort zone. Further north, impulsive lovebirds Rob and Hilary are also looking for a family home. They've not even been together for a couple of years, but are already well on their way to baby number two. With Hilary pregnant for a second time, their two-bed flat is bursting at the seams. But with just 250,000 pounds to spend, this growing family is finding property hunting in the ever-popular Hertfordshire town of Hitchin a real struggle. Can Phil get them more bang for their buck in their dream location, or help them see the light and leave Hitchin behind for a family home that works for everyone?

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E2 Devon Local newlyweds Sam and Jamie want Kirstie's help to put a difficult couple of years behind them and start afresh in a new home, but without moving too far from where they currently live. With the emotional strain of spending the money left to them by Jamie's parents weighing heavily on their shoulders, this search even has Kirstie reaching for her hanky. Can she help them spend their 350,000 pounds wisely and help them find a future home that fits their bill and would've made Jamie's mum and dad proud? Phil's task is no less stressful, and in some ways way bigger. Football coach Geoff, his wife Sharon, their squad of kids and Sharon's mum are all set to move to Torquay for a new life - all they need is the house. With a combined pot of 500,000 pounds, they need a home that meets the needs of a multi-generational family. But that's far from being the biggest of Phil's worries. Having never viewed a single house together before, Geoff and Sharon soon learn that whatever else they have in common, their taste in houses is a million miles apart. With tensions reaching boiling point, can Phil bring all three generations together and find this family one house that suits them all?

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E3 Tyne And Tees Karen and Chris are delighted to be back in the North East with brand-new baby daughter Amelia, but struggling to find a house that matches up to their dreams of family living. For now they're squatting at Karen's mum and dad's and desperate for their own space. But can Kirstie and Phil help them navigate the stagnant market in the villages around Darlington? They'll get a whole lot more house for their 350,000-pounds budget in the North East than in London, but are they really ready to swap the bright lights of the big city for the good life around the village green? Kris and Heather know that buying a house is the next step in their relationship, and hope that marriage and kids won't be far behind, but they are slightly anxious about making such grown-up moves. Add to that a dose of chronic uncertainty about where they want to be for the next stage of their lives and it's clear Kirstie and Phil will have their work cut out finding them a house. With the whole of the North East to choose from, Kris and Heather are struggling to decide if they want to spend their 205,000-pounds budget on city, country or coastal living. Are they ready to put their city days behind them and get a bigger house outside Newcastle or will they sacrifice space to keep the lifestyle they know and love? Can Phil and Kirstie help these two couples find property perfection in their beloved North East? Will their househunters be moving on and moving in to new family homes or will they be staying where they are, stuck in property limbo?

programme.title: Location Location Location

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E1 Harrow And Herts Rupreet and Sundeep are still living at home following their wedding 18 months ago, and have managed to save a healthy deposit for their future family home. Trouble is, Rupreet is a self-confessed postcode snob and she's taken her obsession with location to the limit. When she turns up to meet Kirstie armed with a map and a set of highlighters, you know there is going to be trouble. With a 380,000-pounds budget, they should be able to find a house to fit - if Rupreet can be persuaded to look past her postcode comfort zone. Further north, impulsive lovebirds Rob and Hilary are also looking for a family home. They've not even been together for a couple of years, but are already well on their way to baby number two. With Hilary pregnant for a second time, their two-bed flat is bursting at the seams. But with just 250,000 pounds to spend, this growing family is finding property hunting in the ever-popular Hertfordshire town of Hitchin a real struggle. Can Phil get them more bang for their buck in their dream location, or help them see the light and leave Hitchin behind for a family home that works for everyone?

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E2 Devon Local newlyweds Sam and Jamie want Kirstie's help to put a difficult couple of years behind them and start afresh in a new home, but without moving too far from where they currently live. With the emotional strain of spending the money left to them by Jamie's parents weighing heavily on their shoulders, this search even has Kirstie reaching for her hanky. Can she help them spend their 350,000 pounds wisely and help them find a future home that fits their bill and would've made Jamie's mum and dad proud? Phil's task is no less stressful, and in some ways way bigger. Football coach Geoff, his wife Sharon, their squad of kids and Sharon's mum are all set to move to Torquay for a new life - all they need is the house. With a combined pot of 500,000 pounds, they need a home that meets the needs of a multi-generational family. But that's far from being the biggest of Phil's worries. Having never viewed a single house together before, Geoff and Sharon soon learn that whatever else they have in common, their taste in houses is a million miles apart. With tensions reaching boiling point, can Phil bring all three generations together and find this family one house that suits them all?

programme.title: Location Location Location
programme.desc: S14 E3 Tyne And Tees Karen and Chris are delighted to be back in the North East with brand-new baby daughter Amelia, but struggling to find a house that matches up to their dreams of family living. For now they're squatting at Karen's mum and dad's and desperate for their own space. But can Kirstie and Phil help them navigate the stagnant market in the villages around Darlington? They'll get a whole lot more house for their 350,000-pounds budget in the North East than in London, but are they really ready to swap the bright lights of the big city for the good life around the village green? Kris and Heather know that buying a house is the next step in their relationship, and hope that marriage and kids won't be far behind, but they are slightly anxious about making such grown-up moves. Add to that a dose of chronic uncertainty about where they want to be for the next stage of their lives and it's clear Kirstie and Phil will have their work cut out finding them a house. With the whole of the North East to choose from, Kris and Heather are struggling to decide if they want to spend their 205,000-pounds budget on city, country or coastal living. Are they ready to put their city days behind them and get a bigger house outside Newcastle or will they sacrifice space to keep the lifestyle they know and love? Can Phil and Kirstie help these two couples find property perfection in their beloved North East? Will their househunters be moving on and moving in to new family homes or will they be staying where they are, stuck in property limbo?

When her mum offers to take the children for the summer, she's relieved. But she's devastated when she gets a letter that says her mum has petitioned and been awarded full custody of her kids. In an effort to win them back, she gets a job near the reservation where her mother lives. One day, she reaches out to a childhood friend named Marvin, who's also in a custody battle. When they meet, there's an instant connection. Although she's not in love with Marvin, Tamara feels sympathy for him and falls into a relationship with him. She moves in with him after a few months of dating but immediately becomes the target of his terrible temper. After enduring his verbal and physical abuse, she decides they're through but when she tries to leave him, it ignites a violent confrontation, ending with Marvin dead on the floor from a stab wound. programme.title: CI Australia: Families Of Crime
programme.desc: S1 E1 Carl Williams The notorious baby-faced underworld figure, who police believe killed 10 people, was bashed to death in maximum-security prison while serving 35 years after pleading guilty to the murders of Mark Malia (August 2003), Jason Moran (June 2003) and Lewis Moran (March 2004). He had previously been found guilty of the murder of Michael Marshall, who was shot dead outside his Toorak home in October 2003. The murders occurred at the height of Melbourne's notorious gangland war that raged between 1998 and 2006, leaving 27 dead. Williams' mother, Barbara, publicly defended her son after his jailing and berated the trial judge. The Moran family had dominated Melbourne's criminal world for more than a decade when Williams vowed to wipe them out. In November 2007, Carl's father, George, was jailed for a minimum of 20 months for a massive drug trafficking operation which he carried out with his son. Over two and half years, Carl made about $500,000 selling methamphetamine. George, now 63, lives in suburban Broadmeadows, Melbourne, and suffers from chronic heart disease, diabetes, anxiety and depression. Barbara committed suicide at her Essendon home in December 2008, and their other son Shane died of a heroin overdose aged 31.

programme.title: Ice Road Truckers
programme.desc: S8 E11 Journey To The End Of The Earth For two months out of every year, a group of exceptional men find their way to the Canadian tundra to undertake one of the most dangerous jobs on earth. In the thick of winter, truckers in giant eighteen wheelers carry vital equipment and supplies to miners hundreds of miles away. In blizzard conditions, these truckers travel over ice roads that often take them over frozen lakes. Each man is trained in self survival, from fixing his truck in sub zero conditions in seconds to escaping from a truck if the ice cracks. On the other end of the journey are miners whose lives depend on the truckers making it to their base, year after year. The episodes will form a narrative arch - taking the viewer on a journey from when the experienced and novice truckers first sign up for the season, to the last truck making it back to base.

programme.title: American Restoration
programme.desc: S4 E20 Call The Count Rick Dale, one of Pawn Stars' most popular experts, runs Las Vegas based Rick's Restorations, a family business that finds, restores and upcycles cool objects ranging from Cadillacs to Coke Machines. The before and after reveals of his work are always highlights, in part because of the history nuggets Rick Dale shares about each object, whether it's a barber chair or a gas pump. In this spinoff series, featuring the dynamic characters at Rick's workplace, viewers will watch a variety of objects be bought, bartered and transformed, learning the process of restoration; how do you duplicate Coke machine red? Where can you find 1920s tires? A storyteller who works with tools instead of a pen, Rick shares when and why objects were invented, who used them and how fixing or transforming them changes their value.

Just above the town is a family making a prize-winning Cornish vodka, which Rick uses to make a delicious pancake with a wild blackberry compote and Cornish clotted cream.

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S1 E8 Episode 8 On the wild north Atlantic coast, Rick heads out to sea to go fishing for lobsters with his old friend and celebrity chef Nathan Outlaw, and learns about a revolutionary new conservation programme which is making lobster fishing a sustainable enterprise. In the historic and pretty harbour town of Port Isaac, Rick and Nathan cook up a fabulous Lobster risotto. At Tresillian House, near Newquay, Rick meets with head gardener John Harris, to find out more about his Victorian walled garden, an oasis of calm, where Rick discovers how harvesting by the phases of the moon means better tasting veg. Rick cooks a Cornish Briam, a tasty slow-cooked dish of fresh vegetables.

As they tour the country picking up ingredients, Gordon shows the others how to dress like real Scotsmen. They go in search of amazing Scottish beef, go hunting for scallops and attempt some Highland Games, with hilarious results. As they set off in Gordon's Land Rover, he explains that if the meal he is planning is successful, he will be officially welcomed into Clan Ramsay, so he needs everything to be perfect.

Celebrated pastry chef and famous chocolatier, Tibballs presents an array of incredibly clever and innovative tricks, tips and cheats to bring the wow factor to home baking. Kirsten believes chocolate is the key to happiness, and with a selection of delectable desserts easy to recreate in home kitchens, she may just be right. Kirsten is sharing recipes and techniques for everything from a next-level take on white chocolate & peanut parfait to her rich chocolate flan. In series three of The Chocolate Queen, Tibballs shares a wealth of knowledge as she works through a huge range of recipes, ensuring even beginner bakers can successfully enjoy her creations at home.

London's busy West End attracts millions of visitors every year, and Mary is joining them as she seeks out the secrets of getting busy people fed quickly and well. She'll discover the art of high speed wok cooking in Chinatown, sample the delicious sweet treats being made daily from London's first ever Patisserie before catching a show and a late-night cocktail with some of its cast. In her own kitchen, Mary creates dishes inspired by her trip; an Asian Beef & Pepper Stir Fry knocked up in no time, a heavenly Chocolate Cappuccino Pie and an easy, speedy breakfast for those on the go!

programme.title: Rick Stein's Cornwall
programme.desc: S2 E10 Episode 10 In our fields and hedgerows are plants that are delicious, and plants that are deadly, as Rick learns from a professional forager who takes him on a tour around the beautiful Camel Estuary. Inspired, Rick creates his own version of a Greek 'Horta' pie with foraged greens. Then it's a trip down memory lane with his long-time fish supplier Matthew Stevens who remembers Cornwall before the tourists came. Over a pint with actor, comedian and passionate Cornishman Ed Rowe, star of the BAFTA winning film Bait, Rick examines the impact of second home ownership on Cornish communities.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E3 French Guillaume Brahimi from Guillaume at Bennelong, at the Sydney Opera House, gives a guide to essential fresh ingredients, from herbs to vegetables, then shows how to cook the perfect steak and the potatoes that are a staple through Parisian bistros. Philippe Mouchel (Philippe Mouchel at The Brasserie, Melbourne) makes a lamb navarin served with a celeriac and truffle puree. Maeve meets cheese expert Eric Moschietto from La Bergerie cheese shop in Melbourne and learns that there are so many French cheeses, you can taste three a day for a year and still have some to try. Top food stylist Marie Helene Clauson draws on family recipes to create a light cheese souffle, and charcuterer Romeo Badouin explains terrines, pates and confit. We meet the food and beverage manager at the Sofitel Hotel Sydney, Laurent Branover, and learn that every French family has a crepe pan and uses it every Sunday to make simple crepes, or crepes Suzette served with orange Cointreau butter and flamed.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E4 Indonesian Maeve plunges into the vibrant, spicy world of Indonesian food with chef Rohanna Halim, who heads an all-women kitchen team at her restaurant Ratu Sari in suburban Sydney. She shows the key ingredients needed for Indonesian cooking, including many fresh herbs and spices now widely available. Rohanna makes a spicy chilli sauce called belado which goes perfectly with everything from prawns to vegetables. Fellow head chef and owner Alina Lucas from Jimbaran Restaurant cooks an easy chicken curry, while Java Restaurant's 'Aunty' Wahwan whips up grilled fish with a sweet-and-sour vegetable sauce. A real prince, Tjok Gde Kerthyasa, from Bali's royal family, cooks a traditional duck on the good old Aussie barbie and serves it with a fresh sambal. Also on the barbecue is a superb satay from an expatriate Dutch-Indonesian, Paul Rast. To finish, young Indonesian-Australian Ben Mochtar makes his favourite childhood dessert: eis cendol. It features shaved ice, tropical fruit, coconut milk and 'worms' made from mung bean flour.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E5 Maltese This program explores a different take on Mediterranean cooking with the rustic delights of Maltese food. Chef Paul Camilleri (Restaurant Sojourn) goes through the essential ingredients and then cooks his family recipe for the national dish of rabbit stew. Then it's time for the national snack food, pastizzi, and the national sandwich called Hobz Biz Zejt: tomato paste on crusty bread and topped with anchovies, capers, and olive oil. Chef Louis Bigeni shows how the Maltese have modified recipes from their neighbours, taking pasta to a different level with a rich meat sauce and baked in pastry. We learn about the soft ricotta-style cheeses and harder mature cheese loved by the Maltese, and meet Polly Vella, who missed them so much when she came to Australia that she decided to learn how to make them herself. Finally, broadcaster Rita O'Dwyer from the Maltese radio program makes dessert.

programme.title: Food Safari
programme.desc: S2 E6 Pakistani Some Pakistani dishes are loved around the world, like biryani, the layered, spiced rice and meat dish. Chef Sonya Kayani makes a marvellous version of biryani using goat curry, which she layers with saffron and plain basmati rice. Restaurateur Basil Daniell runs through the key ingredients, herbs and spices, and shares a very easy lamb dumpling recipe adapted with wonton wrappers. We explore a very busy Pakistani eatery and discover the big favourites are tandoori chicken and a slow-cooked lamb and dahl dish called haleem. We meet Pakistani fast bowler Waqar Younis, who shows how Pakistani people love to eat with bread.
